                    <h3>üî§ Umlauts</h3>
                    <p><strong>√§</strong> - like "e" in "bed"<br>
                        Example: M√§dchen (girl)<br><br>
                        <strong>√∂</strong> - round lips and say "e"<br>
                        Example: sch√∂n (beautiful)<br><br>
                        <strong>√º</strong> - like "ew" in "few"<br>
                        Example: √ºber (over)
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="grammar-card">
                    <h3>üí® CH Sound</h3>
                    <p><strong>Soft ch</strong> (after e, i)<br>
                        Like "h" in "huge"<br>
                        Example: ich, nicht<br><br>
                        <strong>Hard ch</strong> (after a, o, u)<br>
                        Guttural sound<br>
                        Example: Bach, noch
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="grammar-card">
                    <h3>üéµ Other Sounds</h3>
                    <p><strong>w</strong> = English "v"<br>
                        Wasser (water)<br><br>
                        <strong>v</strong> = English "f"<br>
                        Vater (father)<br><br>
                        <strong>z</strong> = "ts"<br>
                        Zeit (time)<br><br>
                        <strong>sch</strong> = "sh"<br>
                        Schule (school)
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="grammar-card">
                    <h3>üì¢ R Sound</h3>
                    <p>The German "r" is special!<br><br>
                        It's rolled or guttural<br>
                        (from the back of throat)<br><br>
                        Examples:<br>
                        rot, Brot, drei</p>
                </div>
            </div>

